value.value: A glioblastoma that is characterized by the expression of several gene types that are also typical of the brain's normal, noncancerous nerve cells, or neurons.
A syndrome that is characterized by mental retardation, cataracts, coloboma, kyphosis, and coarse facial features and has_material_basis_in mutation in the SRD5A3 gene.
A mucopolysaccharidosis characterized by a deficiency in hyaluronidase.
A nutritional deficiency disease that is characterized by thinning of the hair (often with loss of hair color), and red scaly rash around the eyes, nose, and mouth.
A steroid inherited metabolic disorder that is characterized by adrenal insufficiency and variable degrees of hyper or hypo androgyny manifestations resulting from steroidogenic enzyme deficiency.

A spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia that is characterized by short stature, short and bowed lower limbs, mild brachydactyly, kyphoscoliosis, abnormal gait, enlarged knee joints, precocious osteoarthropathy, and normal intelligence.

label.value: spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia with congenital joint dislocations

value.value: A spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia that is characterized by short stature of prenatal onset, joint dislocations (knees, hips, radial heads), club feet, and limitation of range of motion that can involve all large joints.

A syndrome that is characterized by brachydactyly, hyperphalangism of digits, facial dysmorphism, dental anomalies, sensorineural hearing loss, delayed motor and mental development, and growth retardation and has_material_basis_in homozygous mutation in the CHSY1 gene.
A syndrome that is characterized by inverted facial expressions in association with a severe and early-onset form of dysfunctional urinary voiding.
An age related macular degeneration that is characterized by progressive vision loss usually to the point of legal blindness.
A vitamin B12 deficiency that is characterized by a lack of vitamin B12 intestinal absorption resulting from a deficiency in the B12 transport protein TCII.
A heart conduction disease that is characterized by the impairment of the conduction between the atria and ventricles of the heart.
An atrioventricular block that is characterized by prolonged PR interval on electrocardiogram caused by delayed conduction from atria to ventricles through the atrioventricular node.

An atrioventricular block that is characterized by progressive prolongation of the PR interval on consecutive beats followed by a blocked P wave on electrocardiogram or intermittently non-conducted P waves not preceded by PR changes on electrocardiogram caused by a conduction block between the atria and the ventricles through the atrioventricular node.

An atrioventricular block that is characterized by bradycardia, hypotension, hemodynamic instability and complete dissociation between P waves and QRS complexes on electrocardiogram caused when conduction fails to propagate from atria to ventricles.
A heart conduction disease that is characterized by dysfunction of the impulse-generating (pacemaker) tissue located in the right atrium of the heart which generates normal sinus rhythm.
A heart disease that is located_in the innermost layer of tissue that lines the chambers of the heart.
A heart valve disease that is characterized by valvular insufficiency or valvular stenosis, located_in tricuspid valve between the right atrium and right ventricle.

A heart valve disease that is characterized by repeated inflammation with fibrinous repair caused by an autoimmune reaction to Group A beta-hemolytic streptococci (GAS) that results in valvular damage. The cardinal anatomic changes of the valve include leaflet thickening, commissural fusion, and shortening and thickening of the tendinous cords.
A vascular disease that is located_in an artery.
A cardiovascular system disease that is located_in the fibrous sac surrounding the heart.
An artery disease that is characterized by build up of plaque in the arteries that carry blood to your head, organs, and limbs.

label.value: familial encephalopathy with neuroserpin inclusion bodies

value.value: A neurodegenerative disease that is characterized by intraneuronal inclusions of mutant neuroserpin resulting in progressive encephalopathy, dementia and seizures and has_material_basis_in a mutation in the SERPINI1 gene inherited in an in autosomal dominant pattern.
An inherited metabolic disorder involving dysfunction of pyrimidine metabolism.
A pyrimidine metabolic disorder that is characterized by an excessive secretion of orotic acid in urine.
A syndrome that is characterized by a pattern of congenital anomalies including choanal atresia and malformations of the heart, inner ear, and retina.
A dystonia that affects most or all of the body.
A dystonia that is localized to a specific part of the body.
A dystonia that involves two or more unrelated body parts.
A dystonia that affects two or more adjacent parts of the body.
A focal dystonia that is characterized by the failure of the pelvic floor muscles to relax during defecation.

A focal dystonia that is characterized by simultaneous contraction of the agonist and antagonist muscles that control the position of the head contracting during dystonic movement which causes the neck to involuntarily turn to the left, right, upwards, and/or downwards.
A focal dystonia that affects a single muscle or small group of muscles in the hand resulting from involuntary muscular contractions.
A focal dystonia that is characterized by a prolonged involuntary upward deviation of the eyes.
A focal dystonia that is characterized by distortions of the mouth and tongue.
A focal dystonia that involves the muscles that control the vocal cords, resulting in strained or breathy speech.
A focal dystonia that is characterized as dystonia that affects the muscles of the head, face, and neck.
A multifocal dystonia that involves the arm and leg on the same side of the body.
A sleep disorder characterized by repeated cessation and commencing of breathing that repeatedly disrupts sleep.

A sleep apnea that is characterized by repeated collapse and obstruction of the upper airway during sleep, which results in reduced airflow (hypopnea) or complete airflow cessation (apnea), oxygen desaturation, and arousals from sleep.
An ampulla of Vater neoplasm that is characterized by glandular dysplastic lesion having pre-malignant potential.

A brain disease that is characterized by functional impairment of cognition, cerebral signal conduction, neurotransmission and synaptic plasticity, and underlying structural pathology associated with diabetes.
A glomerulonephritis that is characterized by hardening of the glomerulus in the kidney.
An ischemia that is characterized by low blood supply to tissues in the limb due to interruption in the arterial blood supply.
A venous insufficiency that is characterized by lower extremity swelling, hyperpigmentation, pruritus and venous ulceration caused by blood pooling in the veins.

A syndrome characterized by episodic skin rash, arthralgias, and fever associated with late-onset sensorineural deafness and renal amyloidosis that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the NLRP3 gene on chromosome 1q44.
A kidney disease that is characterized by progressive detrimental connective tissue deposition of the kidney parenchyma leading to deterioration of renal function.
A specific developmental disorder that is characterized by a pattern of angry mood, defiant behavior and vindictiveness in children and adolescents.
A syndrome that is characterized by sensorineural hearing loss and ovarian failure.
A syndrome that is characterized by advanced bone age, failure to thrive, respiratory problems, dysmorphic facial features, and variable mental retardation.
